Right now your Function is just forwarding raw JSON.
If you want to punch into the body (e.g., read eventId, docId, correlationId) before calling the Message API, you can use Jackson.

Here’s a safe snippet that you can drop in MessageRelayFunction before calling MessageApiRelay.send(...).

⸻

Example: Parse body → extract fields

import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import java.util.UUID;

Inside run(...) before the MessageApiRelay.send(...):

// Parse JSON body (safe)
ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
String corr = firstNonBlank(correlationId, messageId, invocationId); // default

try {
    JsonNode root = mapper.readTree(body);

    // Example: if JSON has "correlationId"
    if (root.hasNonNull("correlationId")) {
        corr = root.get("correlationId").asText();
    }

    // Example: log eventId/docId if present
    String eventId = root.path("event").path("eventId").asText(null);
    String docId   = root.path("event").path("docId").asText(null);

    log.info("[Relay] Parsed body corr=" + corr
            + " eventId=" + safe(eventId)
            + " docId=" + safe(docId));

} catch (Exception jex) {
    log.warning("[Relay] Failed to parse JSON body: " + jex.getMessage()
            + " | using fallback correlationId=" + corr);
}

Helper:

private static String safe(String s) {
    return (s == null || s.isBlank()) ? "-" : s;
}


⸻

What this does
	•	Uses Jackson to parse the Service Bus message body.
	•	Extracts:
	•	correlationId (if present in JSON)
	•	eventId and docId (nested under event)
	•	Falls back gracefully if JSON is missing or invalid.
	•	Logs the important pieces for troubleshooting.

⸻

✅ With this, you can still forward the full body unchanged to the Message API, and you also have access to selected fields (e.g., for logging, headers, metrics).

